br />need to look up all the inode information etc).<br /><br />However, it's not implemented very well, and as a result the directory <br />cache gets out of sync with the real information when I upload things to <br />the site. I _used_ to be able to fix that with "dir -XYZ", but it seems <br />that that doesn't update the cache any more, so now the directory cache <br />only gets updated when the automatic update scripts run.<br /><br />You can just "get" the file anyway, and you should get the correct file <br />unless you happened to ftp in when my uploads were still in progress (but <br />that's pretty unlikely: there's a reasonably fast network between the <br />university and the ftp.funet.fi file, so my uploads seldom take more than <br />a half a minute or something like that).<br /><br />If you are still nervous, you can always try out ftp.cs.helsinki.fi, which<br />doesn't do that kind of caching, and actually gets the kernels about 2<br />minutes before ftp.funet.fi does ;-). However, that site _should_ be<br />considered a secondary site because it's a lot smaller than ftp.funet.fi<br />(ftp.funet.fi is a large site with local RAID disks, a powerful alpha CPU<br />etc, while ftp.cs.helsinki.fi is just a cluster of three normal pentiums<br />running Linux that get the files over NFS over normal ethernet). <br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
